# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Samarkand-class carrier was the Draconis Combine's first purpose-built fleet carrier, conceived as a mobile aerospace platform capable of projecting fighter superiority across entire star systems. Designed at the personal direction of the Coordinator during a period of escalating military tension, the class was fast-tracked into production to meet an urgent strategic need for dedicated carrier capability. Unlike multi-role warships that balanced transport and combat, the Samarkand was optimized around its massive internal fighter bays, with defensive weapons and armor serving primarily to protect the vessel long enough for its aerospace wings to dominate the battlespace. The design philosophy emphasized speed and fighter capacity over raw firepower, making the Samarkand dependent on escort warships for protection against capital-class opponents. Despite this intended role, Combine admirals frequently deployed Samarkands as assault vanguards -- a tactical misuse that cost the navy dearly whenever the carriers found themselves engaged without adequate escorts.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Displacing 350,000 tons across 501 meters of hull, the Samarkand is built around its fighter operations. The Block I carries seventy-two aerospace fighters in two bays of thirty-six, supported by twelve small craft for utility and search-and-rescue operations. Three docking collars accommodate DropShip attachments, while over 46,000 tons of cargo capacity provides logistical depth for extended deployments. Twin gravity decks measuring 150 and 60 meters allow comfortable crew rotation across its complement of officers, enlisted personnel, gunners, and a thirty-strong marine detachment. The Block I's capital armament centers on a single Medium Naval PPC in the nose and a Light Naval PPC on each broadside, supplemented by a NAC/10 naval autocannon in each forward quarter. Naval laser batteries of NL35s and NL45s cover the flanks and aft, while extensive conventional weapons including LRM-20 and LRM-10 racks, SRM-4 launchers, medium and large lasers, and machine guns provide layered anti-aerospace defense. However, a known vulnerability exists near the large engine mounts in the lower rear, creating limited aft firing arcs. The Block II upgrade authorized in 2668 dramatically increased combat capability: ferro-carbide armor replaced standard plating, a Heavy Naval PPC replaced each Light NPPC on the broadsides, NAC/20s replaced NAC/10s in the forward quarters, and additional NL35s and LRM-20 racks were added to the nose and aft-quarter arcs. Heat sinks nearly doubled to 1,700, a fourth docking collar was added, and the marine complement was expanded to one hundred.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>Block II Samarkands entered service beginning in 2668 under Coordinator Urizen II's naval expansion program, their upgraded ferro-carbide armor and heavier capital weapons making them significantly more capable than their Block I predecessors. The DCS New Samarkand served as a prominent Block II carrier within the Draconis Combine Admiralty, emblematic of the enhanced variant's role in the Combine's growing fleet. By 2765, eight Samarkands of both blocks operated across the Third and Fourth Fleets of the DCMS naval arm. Most were destroyed during the devastating Liberation of Terra campaign that ended the Star League. Three confirmed Samarkands survived to join General Kerensky's Operation Exodus -- the Beijing, Deal Breaker, and Yorktown -- carrying their fighter wings into the unknown and eventually serving with the Clans.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Samarkand-class carrier was born from Coordinator Hehiro Kurita's vision of a dedicated fleet carrier that would give the Draconis Combine independent aerospace superiority across its vast borders. Launched from the yards of Tengoku no Ken Master Shipwrights Ltd. on Mizunami in 2579, the class was fast-tracked into production as the Reunification War became inevitable. The first two vessels, DCS Samarkand and DCS Benjamin, loaded their full seventy-two-fighter complements and jumped into combat against the Outworlds Alliance in June 2581, proving the carrier concept in the crucible of the Periphery campaigns. By 2585, the DCS Dieron and DCS Alshain had joined the fleet, serving through the remainder of the Reunification War. One Block I was lost during the Outworlds campaign, leaving three survivors.</p><p>In peacetime, the surviving carriers assisted Combine colonial expansion and performed ceremonial duties, including escorting Coordinator Sanethia to Luthien in 2619. In 2668, Coordinator Urizen II authorized the Block II upgrade, incorporating ferro-carbide armor to dramatically increase protection, replacing the Light Naval PPCs with Heavy variants, and upgrading NAC/10 naval autocannons to the more powerful NAC/20. Multitudes of both blocks were built before the end of the Star League era, with many serving as escorts for SLDF operations.</p><p>By 2765, eight Samarkands operated across the Third and Fourth Fleets of the DCMS naval arm, with the DCS Hagiwawa serving as flagship of the Third Fleet. The class carried a known vulnerability near its large engine mounts in the lower rear, which created limited aft firing arcs that opponents learned to exploit. More damaging was the tactical misuse of Samarkands as assault vanguards -- a role they were never designed to fill. Without adequate escort warships, the carriers were easily overcome by heavier opponents, and the Combine lost several vessels to this doctrinal error.</p><p>The Liberation of Terra campaign destroyed most of the class, though three confirmed vessels -- Beijing, Deal Breaker, and Yorktown -- survived to join General Kerensky's Operation Exodus. During the First Succession War, the DCS Hagiwawa participated in the invasion of the Federated Suns, and at the Battle of Clovis in May 2787, the Hagiwawa's flotilla engaged AFFS warships for six hours, suffering heavy damage before prevailing. The remaining Samarkands were posted along the Lyran Commonwealth and Federated Suns borders, where attrition gradually consumed the survivors. The shipyard at Mizunami was destroyed during the Second Succession War, eliminating any possibility of building replacements. Only the DCS Togura survived to the modern era, deteriorating into a barely functional orbital museum above New Samarkand -- a silent monument to the Combine's once-formidable carrier fleet.</p>
</history>

